INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('38', '50', '11', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Digital Innovation Prize Winners\",\"slug\":\"digital-innovation-prize-winners\",\"postDate\":1382321470,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>The Faculty of Architecture, Design and Planning is pleased to announce two of its Master of Architecture students have won the Prize for Digital Innovation in the 2013 Australian Institute of Architects Student Awards.<\\/p><p>Jonathan Fernandes and James Ye-Won Lee\'s digital project presented the temporary structure and interior of a moveable theatre space. Able to be assembled and disassembled in 72 hours, the theatre is designed to appear alongside Sydney Festival\'s iconic Spiegeltent.<\\/p><p>\\\"You can pack it away, put it in a truck, move it somewhere else in a different location and put it up,\\\" says James<\\/p><p>\\\"It can be placed in different sites,\\\" says Jonathan<\\/p><p>The design allows the theatre\'s sounds and lights to guide audiences\' movements in and around the space. Audiences find themselves plunged deep in the immersive environment of the theatre.<\\/p><p>Their model\'s exceptional interactive ceiling was what set them apart.<\\/p><p>\\\"The ceiling can adapt depending on the type of theatre performance, \\\" says Jonathan.<\\/p><p>\\\"If you need the theatre to be more open, the ceiling could raise up if more people need to be accommodated, and it could lower to create a more intimate space.\\\"<\\/p><p>Entrants from three other universities offering architecture in NSW were in the running for the Digital Innovation Prize. This achievement for Faculty of Architecture, Design and Planning students Jonathan and James is \\\"great exposure,\\\" says Jonathan.<\\/p><p>The Faculty of Architecture, Design and Planning congratulates James and Jonathan on their outstanding success.<\\/p>\",\"13\":\"\",\"7\":[\"49\"],\"14\":\"\",\"1\":\"Faculty students awarded Prize for Digital Innovation\",\"15\":\"\",\"18\":\"\",\"16\":\"\",\"17\":\"\",\"3\":\"\",\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-21 02:11:10', '2013-10-21 02:11:10', 'bc192a12-571e-420c-9a66-353d77f9a2b0');
INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('39', '17', '10', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Making your BB10 app high resolution\",\"slug\":\"interaction-design-item\",\"postDate\":1381650600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. This is because the BB10 has a high pixel density ratio and web content seems to be rendered by default at a low dpi. The effect is that all of the elements in your app look enlarged. <em>Note that this only happens when you explicitly set the width and height css elements on the &lt;body&gt; to 768px and 1280px respectively.<\\/em><\\/p><p>For most people who have not set the width and height of their &lt;body&gt; or any elements it contains to a certain pixel value and have instead set them to either 100% or just let the elements fill the space, this enlargement issue won\\u2019t happen. What will happen is that your app will render at about 160 pixels per inch. The BB10 however is capable of a resolution of <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/developer.blackberry.com\\/devzone\\/design\\/devices_and_screen_sizes.html\\\">356 ppi<\\/a>. That means you are missing out on utilising the full resolution of the device and making a really great looking app.<\\/p><p>The solution is to adjust the \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag slightly. Usually we have had an attribute called \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d that we set to 1.0 meaning that the app is neither zoomed in or out. To adjust for the higher pixel density in the BB10 we want to zoom out slightly. This means setting the \\u201cinitial-scale\\u201d to about 0.446.<\\/p><p>So your \\u201cviewport\\u201d meta tag should now look like this:<\\/p><p>&lt;meta name=\\u201dviewport\\u201d content=\\u201dwidth=device-width,initial-scale=0.446,user-scalable=no\\u201d&gt;<\\/p><p>You may have to adjust your html elements to suit the new resolution of your app. However it will be worth the effort when you end up with a much better looking app.<\\/p><p><strong>Reference:<\\/strong> <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/supportforums.blackberry.com\\/t5\\/Web-and-WebWorks-Development\\/How-to-set-up-the-viewport-for-a-BlackBerry-WebWorks-application\\/ta-p\\/1943807\\\">How to set up the viewport for a BlackBerry WebWorks application for BlackBerry 10<\\/a><\\/p>\",\"5\":\"Design Computing\",\"13\":\"\",\"7\":[\"42\"],\"14\":\"\",\"1\":\"Some people have run into an issue with their BB10 app looking oversized when they tested on the actual device. \",\"15\":\"\",\"18\":\"\",\"16\":\"\",\"17\":\"\",\"3\":[\"18\"],\"8\":\"Interaction Design\",\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-21 02:28:21', '2013-10-21 02:28:21', '26aa17ae-3e5f-4c87-90d6-7132f7d2ac02');
INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('40', '52', '11', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Ecologies of invention\",\"slug\":\"ecologies-of-invention\",\"postDate\":1382324723,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Imagine the walls of a building letting in and circulating air - not the windows, the walls. This is what architect Doris Kim Sung has achieved in her work through the use of thermo-biometals - metals that curl and shift in response to sunlight and the weather - in the construction of buildings. With a background in biology, Doris based the idea of a \'breathing\' wall on the unique way in which a grasshopper takes in air through its sides and uses the air to cool its body. (You can find more information about Doris Kim Sung and her designs through the TED website: blog.tedx.com\\/post\\/64111337047\\/what-if-building-materials-were-more-like-skin.)<\\/p><p>What kind of person thinks to make this creative connection, from a grasshopper to a building material? How can people across various disciplines be encouraged and trained to make connections such as these; to work more inventively? Traditionally, invention has been seen as isolated to the realm of scientific discovery. But are artists, designers and musicians also inventors? The contributors to Ecologies of invention, (ed. Andy Dong, John Conomos and Brad Buckley) attempt to answer these questions - and ask and answer even more.<\\/p><p>Ecologies of Invention is the first collection of essays that brings together writers and scholars of international standing from the University of Sydney and beyond to examine the assumptions underlying notions of inventiveness. In doing so, an important distinction is made between \'inventiveness\' and \'creativity\'. Significantly, the contributors look at origins, approaches and attitudes towards inventiveness across the disciplines, including art, architecture, design, history, engineering, science, law and economics. As Marc Newson, designer of the famous Lockheed Lounge, points out in the Foreword, Ecologies of invention \'makes an important contribution to our understanding of that \\\"light bulb\\\" moment of realisation or invention that takes place across all disciplines\'. As well as sharing similarities across disciplines, the contributors demonstrate how invention on all different scales, from personal capacities to the social, spatial and network configurations, share similar processes and production.<\\/p><p>Edited by Andy Dong, Professor and ARC Future Fellow at the University of Sydney and holder of the Warren Centre Chair for Engineering Innovation; Brad Buckley, artist, activist, urbanist and Professor of Contemporary Art and Culture at Sydney College of the Arts; and John Conomos, artist, critic and theorist at Sydney College of the Arts, the concept of invention as explored in Ecologies of invention moves beyond the individual chapters and contributions by Faculty of Architecture Academics Lian Loke, Dagmar Reinhardt, Chris Smith and Rob Saunders, to the design of the book itself.<\\/p><p>The book poses new questions for scholars, artists, architects, designers, historians, engineers, scientists, lawyers and economists about the nature, origins and processes of invention.<\\/p><p>If you would like more information about the book, editors or contributors, please contact Sydney University Press at sup.info@sydney.edu.au.<\\/p>\",\"13\":\"\",\"7\":[\"51\"],\"14\":\"\",\"1\":\"Ecologies of Invention is the first collection of essays that brings together writers and scholars of international standing from the University of Sydney and beyond to examine the assumptions underlying notions of inventiveness.\",\"15\":\"\",\"18\":\"\",\"16\":\"\",\"17\":\"\",\"3\":\"\",\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-21 03:05:23', '2013-10-21 03:05:23', '147598a5-b174-4497-bf46-19610932cf4b');
INSERT INTO `craft_entryversions` (`id`, `entryId`, `sectionId`, `creatorId`, `locale`, `notes`, `data`, `dateCreated`, `dateUpdated`, `uid`) VALUES ('41', '54', '11', '1', 'en_us', NULL, '{\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Design Lab Research presented at OzChi Conference\",\"slug\":\"design-lab-research-presented-at-ozchi-conference\",\"postDate\":1382325000,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"2\":\"<p>Cutting-edge research in human-computer interaction is the topic of discussion at the annual OzCHI Conference in Melbourne this year.<\\/p><p>OzCHI brings together researchers from across Australia to build networks, find collaborators and stay abreast of the latest knowledge of the way humans interact with computers.<\\/p><p>Design Lab lecturer and program director of the University\'s <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/sydney.edu.au\\/architecture\\/programs_of_study\\/postgraduate\\/IDEA.shtml\\\">Master of Interaction Design and Electronic Arts (IDEA)<\\/a>, Lian Loke, says that OzChi is one of the best ways to present research and gain inspiration from others\' works.<\\/p><p>\\\"The conference does the equivalent of research speed dating. It gets everyone acquainted with everyone else\'s research,\\\" Loke said.<\\/p><p>\\\"We have also been constructing research trees that show the relationships between areas of research. Understanding these degrees of separation between active research projects lets us easily see where the field is headed.\\\"<\\/p><p>Yesterday, Loke and UTS collaborator Professor Toni Robertson ran a workshop, \'The Body in Design\'. The workshop involved designing for bodily experience and understanding bodily engagement in the design process.<\\/p><p><br><img id=\\\"processed\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.arch.usyd.edu.au\\/images\\/news_events\\/2012\\/eloquentrobes.jpg\\\" align=\\\"right\\\" border=\\\"\\\">\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Design Lab PhD candidate, Ingrid Pohl, will present today a short paper, \'Engaging the sense of touch in interactive architecture\'. The paper explores the ideas manifest in her prototype sensitive surfaces, on display at the Design Lab\'s end of year festival, <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/sydney.edu.au\\/architecture\\/events\\/organisedCacophony.shtml\\\">Organised Cacophony<\\/a>.<\\/p><p>IDEA research student, Claudia Nunez-Pacheco has also presented a poster, \'Eloquent Robes\' that explains the work currently exhibited at Organised Cacophony.<\\/p>\",\"13\":\"\",\"7\":[\"53\"],\"14\":\"\",\"1\":\"\\u200bCutting-edge research in human-computer interaction is the topic of discussion at the annual OzCHI Conference in Melbourne this year.\",\"15\":\"\",\"18\":\"\",\"16\":\"\",\"17\":\"\",\"3\":\"\",\"10\":\"\"}}', '2013-10-21 03:10:00', '2013-10-21 03:10:00', '90318ee0-55ed-4fd1-a768-f543e6534c81');
